column12: Reconstructing cardiac frequency phenomena in angiographic data
column13: Techniques are provided for reconstructing cardiac frequency phenomena from a sequence of angiographic images, i.e., two-dimensional projection images acquired at faster than cardiac rate (greater than two-fold), and analyzed to provide a spatiotemporal reconstruction of moving vascular pulse waves according to that projection. In aspects, a cardiac frequency bandpass filter and/or a Eulerian magnification may be applied to the angiographic data to output the spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena.

The discovery that contrast in blood vessels varies at cardiac frequency in magnitude and phase enables a set of processes for increasing the signal to noise ratio or equivalently the informational content of an angiogram. In this invention, the organization of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase enables equivalent information on anatomy and physiology to be obtained with less dose of injected chemical contrast agent, less x-ray dose, and/or less navigation of the injecting catheter within blood vessels. The cardiac frequency magnitude and phase is organized so that the arterial and venous subsystems of circulation have coherence at cardiac frequency. This enables processes for diagnosing deficits of circulation that involve alterations in the transit of blood from the arterial to the venous subsystems of circulation. Furthermore, the discovery of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase organization enables the design and manufacture of lighter and more portable angiography equipment.

column12: TEMPORAL CALIBRATION OF AN ANGIOGRAPHIC IMAGING SYSTEM
column13: Angiographic data is obtained by injecting a chemical contrast agent intravascularly, and imaging passage of the contrast as a function of time, thereby generating a sequence of images. To correct error from uncalibrated timestamps embedded in the image metadata, radio-opaque markers are used to generate a watermark embedding timestamp data in obtained images. The radio-opaque markers cause opacification on the x-ray images in the form of dynamic watermarks that encode timestamps. The positions of the markers in the watermark (cast from the radio-opaque markers) are then processed and analyzed to generate an accurate timestamp for the image. By generating an accurate timestamp, synchronized calculations of the images with other data sources are provided.

column12: Spatiotemporal reconstruction of a moving vascular pulse wave from a plurality of lower dimensional angiographic projections
column13: A plurality of image projections are acquired at faster than cardiac rate. A spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena in three spatial dimensions is generated from two dimensional image projections using physiological coherence at cardiac frequency. Complex valued methods may be used to operate on the plurality of image projections to reconstruct a higher dimensional spatiotemporal object. From a plurality of two spatial dimensional angiographic projections, a 3D spatial reconstruction of moving pulse waves and other cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena is obtained. Reconstruction techniques for angiographic data obtained from biplane angiography devices are also provided herein.

column12: Replaceable liner for the discharge assembly of a rotary grinding mill or the like
column13: Replaceable liner for the discharge assembly of a rotary grinding mill or the like is disclosed, in the preferred embodiment, as including first, second, and inner most self-supporting box members. The first box member includes closed sides, bottom, and second end, and includes an open top and first end. The second box member includes closed sides, top, and bottom, and includes open ends. When the grate is removed from the first discharge casting, the second box member can be inserted within the first discharge casting and moved into the second and third discharge castings. Then the first box member can be placed within the first discharge casting. Thus, when the grate is attached to the first discharge casting, the first and second box members will be captured within the first and second discharge castings. The inner most box member is provided for installation in the three inner most castings which form the discharge cone of the discharge assembly. The inner most box member includes closed sides, top, and bottom, and includes open ends. The inner most box member further includes a discharge outlet formed by the top generally extending beyond the open end and terminating in a curved portion which follows and protects the three inner most castings. Further, one of the sides also extends beyond the open end of the inner most box member and terminates in the curved portion of the top such that the sides extend past the open end alternately in the mill and the inner most box members in adjacent tiers of discharge castings form a unitary outlet.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR PROVIDING MAGNETIC TUNNELING JUNCTIONS USABLE IN SPIN TRANSFER TORQUE MAGNETIC MEMORIES
column13: A method and system for providing a magnetic junction are described. The method and system include providing a free layer, a symmetry filter, and a pinned layer. The free layer has a first magnetic moment switchable between stable states when a write current is passed through the magnetic junction. The symmetry filter transmits charge carriers having a first symmetry with higher probability than charge carriers having another symmetry. The pinned layer has a second magnetic moment pinned in a direction. The symmetry filter resides between the free layer and the pinned layer. At least one of the free layer and the pinned layer lies in a plane, has the charge carriers of the first symmetry in a spin channel at a Fermi level, lacks the charge carriers of the first symmetry at the Fermi level in another spin channel, and has a nonzero magnetic moment component perpendicular to the plane.

column13: The present invention is a catheter actuation handle for deflecting a distal end of a tubular catheter body having first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body. The handle comprises a first grip portion, a bearing assembly, and an actuator. The first grip potion includes a pivot with a pathway extending through the pivot. The pathway is generally parallel to a longitudinal centerline of the first grip portion. The bearing assembly is located on the first grip portion proximal to the pivot. The actuator is pivotally coupled to the pivot and includes first and second ends that are laterally offset from the longitudinal centerline and are on opposite sides of the centerline from each other. When the distal end of the handle is coupled to the proximal end of the body, the first and second actuation wires extend along the pathway to the bearing assembly. The bearing assembly diverts the first actuation wire to a first connection point on the actuator and the second actuation wire to a second connection point on the actuator.

column13: The present invention is directed to a bird collision avoidance system, wherein the bird collision avoidance system is installed on an aircraft and comprises a bird detection unit and an associated bird repelling unit, wherein, the bird repelling unit comprises at least one soudn emitter to generate a sound signal having a variable frequency, focussed beam pattern which is directed along a project flight path of an aircraft. The advantage of using sound signal having a focussed beam pattern is that the beam can be focussed substantially directly at a bird in the projected flight path of the aircraft and can be used to repel the bird away from the projected flight path of the aircraft. By focussing the beam only at the bird in the projected flight path of the aircraft, other birds in the vicinity but not in the projected flight path of the aircraft will not hear the sound signal, and, therefore habituation to the sound signal will be slower than with omni-directional noise emitters as known from the prior art. A modulated ultrasound signal signal may be used as the sound signal having a focussed beam pattern. The bird collision avoidance system may also be mounted on wind turbines.

A steerable catheter or sheath includes a catheter or sheath body defining a longitudinal axis; first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body; and a control handle coupled to the body for steering a distal end of the body. The control handle includes a grip portion including a pivot; a wire diverting assembly located on the grip portion at a location separate from the pivot; and an actuator assembly coupled to the pivot and configured for pivotal movement in a single plane. The wire diverting assembly can include first and second actuation wire connection locations that are disposed on opposite sides of the longitudinal axis. The first and second actuation wires can extend toward the wire diverting assembly in a first orientation, and the wire diverting assembly can change the first orientation to a second orientation that is at an angle to the first orientation.

column13: A method and apparatus for destroying a syringe needle, having a housing, first and second walls in opposed relationship in the housing and defining therebetween a needle burn chamber, the distance between the first and second surfaces being at least the length of the needle, the first surface defining a first opening therethrough, needle receiver in the chamber movable between the first and second surfaces and defining a second opening therethrough which is coaxial with the first opening, a first electrical contact on the needle receiver, a first electrical contact on the needle receiver, a second electrical contact on the second surface and being in association with the second opening, power source connected to the first and second contacts, a waste collector disposed in the housing beneath and in communication with the burn chamber, the waste collector being removable from the housing, and spring loaded needle guide for moving the needle receiver toward the first opening; so that when the needle is inserted through the first and second openings to be in contacting relationship to the needle receiver and the needle receiver is moved toward the second surface, the tip of the needle engages the second contact closing the circuit between the contacts and melting the needle along at least most of its length with the resultant melted waste falling into the waste collector.

column12: APPARATUS FOR RADIUS CURVE LOG SAWING AND STRAIGHT CUTTING
column13: A compact radius log sawing apparatus cuts a log longitudinally along a radius curve to produce boards. This sawing apparatus includes a C-shaped housing containing a plurality of radially adjustable paired rollers, and a continuous flexible saw blade provided with teeth at one or both edges. A support exposes a section of saw blade that is curved and stabilized by the use of electromagnetic fields in cooperation with rollers. The saw is then configured to make a cut of a desired thickness in a curve parallel the growth rings of a log, in an arc which minimizes the number of knot defects in the board. The compact radius cutting saw may be modified to provide a straight cut by replacing the curved blade with a conventional band saw blade. This straight cut saw may optionally include a guide/drive wheel assembly positioned within or external to the housing. An extendable and retractable sleeve at each open end of the C-shaped housing is provided to further stabilize the saw blade and provide a gentle flow during its course of travel.

Apparatus and method for removing a needle from a syringe
column13: A method and apparatus for removing the needle portion of a hypodermic syringe and simultaneously sterilizing and destroying the needle portion of a hypodermic syringe, thereby eliminating the risk of infection by microorganisms that may be present in or on the needle. When a syringe is inserted into the apparatus, the needle is heated to a temperature sufficient to melt or at least soften the needle, and sufficient to inactivate any virus, bacteria, yeast, or other microorganism remaining on or within the needle. The needle also is cur at the location of melting so that the needle is removed from the remaining portion of the syringe. The heating and cutting elements are part of a disposable cartridge, which also contains the cut-off needle portions.

column13: The discovery that contrast in blood vessels varies at cardiac frequency in magnitude and phase enables a set of processes for increasing the signal to noise ratio or equivalently the informational content of an angiogram. In this invention, the organization of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase enables equivalent information on anatomy and physiology to be obtained with less dose of injected chemical contrast agent, less x-ray dose, and/or less navigation of the injecting catheter within blood vessels. The cardiac frequency magnitude and phase is organized so that the arterial and venous subsystems of circulation have coherence at cardiac frequency. This enables processes for diagnosing deficits of circulation that involve alterations in the transit of blood from the arterial to the venous subsystems of circulation. Furthermore, the discovery of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase organization enables the design and manufacture of lighter and more portable angiography equipment.

column12: Method and system for providing magnetic tunneling junctions usable in spin transfer torque magnetic memories
column13: A method and system provide a magnetic junction. A free layer, a symmetry filter, and a pinned layer are provided. The free layer has a magnetic moment switchable between stable states when a write current is passed through the magnetic junction. The symmetry filter transmits charge carriers having a first symmetry with higher probability than charge carriers having another symmetry. The symmetry filter resides between the free layer and the pinned layer. The free layer and/or the pinned layer lies in a plane, has the charge carriers of the first symmetry in a spin channel at a Fermi level, lacks the charge carriers of the first symmetry at the Fermi level in another spin channel, and has a nonzero magnetic moment component perpendicular to the plane. The free layer and/or the pinned layer and the symmetry filter has at least one lattice mismatch of less than seven percent.

column13: 혈관 조영도는 일련의 영상들(일반적으로 X-선)을 획득하는 동안 혈관 조영적 화학 조영제가 주입되 혈관에 대한 연구 분야이다. 영상 시퀀스의 조영 패턴은 혈관 해부학 및 생리학에 대한 정보를 제공한다. 심장 주파수에 따라 혈관 조영의 크기와 위상이 변한다는 발견은 심장 주파수 혈관 조영 현상의 시공간적 재구성으로서 시각화될 수 있으며, 신호 대 잡음비 또는 혈관 조영도의 정보 내용을 균등하게 증가시키는 일련의 프로세스를 가능하게 한다. 본 발명에 있어서, 심장 주파수 크기 및 위상의 구성은 더 적은 양의 주입 화학 조영제, 더 적은 X-선 선량 및/또는 혈관내 주입 카테터의 더 적은 탐색으로도 해부학 및 생리학에 대한 동등한 정보를 얻을 수 있게 한다. 심장 주파수 크기와 위상은 순환의 동맥 및 정맥 서브시스템이 심장 주파수에서 간섭성을 갖도록 구성된다. 이것은 동맥으로부터 정맥 순환 서브시스템으로의 혈액 이동의 변경을 포함하는 순환 결핍을 진단하는 프로세스를 가능하게 한다. 또한, 심장 주파수 크기 및 위상 조직의 발견은 더 가볍고 휴대가 간편한 혈관 조영 장비의 설계 및 제조를 가능하게 한다.

Handle - bars; saddle supports.- Relates to arrangements to facilitate the removal, to prevent theft &c., or the adjustment of the handle-bar or saddle support, or to allow the handle - bar to be turned through a right-angle. Fig. 1 shows the invention applied to the handle - bar of a bicycle. A lever h, pivoted in the stem a, carries a projection i, which passes through a hole in the stem and engages holes or recesses in the steering-post. A similar arrangement is applied to the saddle support, and a clip similar to r is provided to facilitate correct adjustment after removal from the saddle pillar.

Spatiotemporal reconstruction of a moving vascular pulse wave from a plurality of lower dimensional angiographic projections
column13: A plurality of image projections are acquired at faster than cardiac rate. A spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena in three spatial dimensions is generated from two dimensional image projections using physiological coherence at cardiac frequency. Complex valued methods may be used to operate on the plurality of image projections to reconstruct a higher dimensional spatiotemporal object. From a plurality of two spatial dimensional angiographic projections, a 3D spatial reconstruction of moving pulse waves and other cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena is obtained. Reconstruction techniques for angiographic data obtained from biplane angiography devices are also provided herein.

column12: Temporal calibration of an angiographic imaging system
column13: Angiographic data is obtained by injecting a chemical contrast agent intravascularly, and imaging passage of the contrast as a function of time, thereby generating a sequence of images. To correct error from uncalibrated timestamps embedded in the image metadata, radio-opaque markers are used to generate a watermark embedding timestamp data in obtained images. The radio-opaque markers cause opacification on the x-ray images in the form of dynamic watermarks that encode timestamps. The positions of the markers in the watermark (cast from the radio-opaque markers) are then processed and analyzed to generate an accurate timestamp for the image. By generating an accurate timestamp, synchronized calculations of the images with other data sources are provided.

column12: Radius curve log sawing apparatus and method
column13: A sawing process and apparatus cuts a log longitudinally along a radius curve to produce boards. The sawing apparatus includes a continuous flexible band saw blade, provided with teeth at one or both edges. A support exposes a section of saw blade that is curved and stabilized by the use of electromagnetic fields in cooperation with rollers. The saw is then configured to make a cut of a desired thickness in a curve parallel the growth rings of a log, in an arc which minimizes the number of knot defects in the board. With each pass of the log through the saw, or vice-versa, a new arc section is cut, and the log or the saw is rotated and positioned for the next arc section cut. Plural sawing stations may be used in series, and the process may be run bi-directionally when using double-edged saw blades. Once the board sections are cut, they are flattened under pressure in a kiln. Triangular grooves may be cut prior to delivery to the kiln, and adhered together afterwards to facilitate the flattening operation for small radius boards.

Composition fuel.-Damp peat is pulped, and then dried in a steam-jacketed vessel in which at the same time it is mixed with from 5 to 7¢ per cent of the hard tar ' described in Specification 4427/06, the product being made into briquettes, for instance in a brick-press. Preferably the hard tar is added hot or molten. Charcoal may be made from the fuel, and also gas to be used in generating the steam for heating the mixer. Fig. 1 shows a mixing- drying apparatus comprising a steam-jacketed pan c containing edge-runner disks e, having projections f on either side alternately; these disks revolve upon a cross-shaft g turned by a central vertical shaft i. One of the shafts carries scrapers (not shown), which precede or follow the disks e, to remove material from the centre and sides of the pan. The bottom of the pan carries a renewable track n for the disks e, and may be made in sections hinged to the sides for discharging the fuel into a hopper below.

column12: INTRINSIC CONTRAST OPTICAL CROSS-CORRELATED WAVELET ANGIOGRAPHY
column13: A time sequenced series of optical images of a patient is obtained at a rate faster than cardiac frequency, wherein the time sequenced series of images capture one or more physical properties of intrinsic contrast. A cross-correlated signal from the patient is obtained. A cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis is applied to the time sequenced series of optical images to yield a spatiotemporal representation of cardiac frequency phenomena. The cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis comprises performing a wavelet transform on the time-sequenced series of optical images to obtain a wavelet transformed signal, cross-correlating the wavelet transformed signal with the cross- correland signal to obtain a cross-correlated signal, filtering the cross-correlated, signal at cardiac frequency to obtain a filtered signal, and performing an inverse wavelet transform on the filtered signal to obtain a spatiotemporal representation of the time sequenced series of optical images. Images of the cardiac frequency phenomena are generated.

column13: A steerable catheter or sheath includes a catheter or sheath body defining a longitudinal axis; first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body; and a control handle coupled to the body for steering a distal end of the body. The control handle includes a grip portion including a pivot; a wire diverting assembly located on the grip portion at a location separate from the pivot; and an actuator assembly coupled to the pivot and configured for pivotal movement in a single plane. The wire diverting assembly can include first and second actuation wire connection locations that are disposed on opposite sides of the longitudinal axis. The first and second actuation wires can extend toward the wire diverting assembly in a first orientation, and the wire diverting assembly can change the first orientation to a second orientation that is at an angle to the first orientation.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR PROVIDING MAGNETIC TUNNELING JUNCTIONS USABLE IN SPIN TRANSFER TORQUE MAGNETIC MEMORIES
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide improved magnetic junctions usable in high-density STT-RAMs.SOLUTION: A method and system provide a magnetic junction. A free layer, a symmetry filter, and a pinned layer are provided. The free layer can have a magnetic moment switchable between stable magnetic states when a readout current passes through the magnetic junction. The symmetry filter transmits charge carriers having a first symmetry with higher probability than charge carriers having another symmetry. The symmetry filter may reside between the free layer and the pinned layer. The free layer and/or the pinned layer lies in a plane, has the charge carriers of the first symmetry in a spin channel at the Fermi level, lacks the charge carriers of the first symmetry at the Fermi level in another spin channel, and has a nonzero magnetic moment component perpendicular to the plane. The free layer and/or the pinned layer and the symmetry filter has at least one lattice mismatch of less than seven percent.

column12: RECONSTRUCTING CARDIAC FREQUENCY PHENOMENA IN ANGIOGRAPHIC DATA
column13: Techniques are provided for reconstructing cardiac frequency phenomena from a sequence of angiographic images, i.e., two-dimensional projection images acquired at faster than cardiac rate (greater than two-fold), and analyzed to provide a spatiotemporal reconstruction of moving vascular pulse waves according to that projection. In aspects, a cardiac frequency bandpass filter and/or a Eulerian magnification may be applied to the angiographic data to output the spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena.

column12: Method and apparatus for electrically destroying a syringe needle
column13: A method and apparatus for sterilizing and destroying a syringe needle includes a rotating needle carriage that receives a needle in a loading position. The needle carriage is rotated downwardly to a cut-off position. At the cut-off position, two opposing contact blades pinch the needle, which electrically connects the positive and negative terminals of a battery. Current flows through the contact blades and the needle, thereby melting the needle. A slight further rotation of the needle carriage causes the contact blades to shear the needle. The sheared portion of the needle then falls into a waste compartment in the bottom of the apparatus. When the syringe is removed from the needle carriage, the needle carriage rotates upwardly and returns to the loading position.

The present invention is directed to a bird collision avoidance system (100, 200), wherein the bird collision avoidance system (100, 200) is installed on an aircraft (102) and comprises a bird detection unit (104) and an associated bird repelling unit (110, 206), wherein, the bird repelling unit (110, 206) comprises at least one sound emitter to generate a sound signal having a variable frequency, focussed beam (114) pattern which is directed along a projected flight path of the aircraft (102). The advantage of using sound signal having a focussed beam pattern is that the beam can be focussed substantially directly at a bird in the projected flight path of the aircraft and can be used to repel the bird away from the projected flight path of the aircraft. By focussing the beam only at the bird in the projected flight path of the aircraft, other birds in the vicinity but not in the projected flight path of the aircraft will not hear the sound signal. A modulated ultrasound signal may be used as the sound signal having a focussed beam pattern. The bird collision avoidance system may also be mounted on wind turbines.

column12: APPARATUS FOR RADIUS CURVE LOG SAWING AND STRAIGHT CUTTING
column13: A compact radius log sawing apparatus (1) cuts a log (2) longitudinally along a radius curve to produce boards. This sawing apparatus (1) includes a C-shaped housing (11) containing a plurality of radially adjustable paired rollers (5, 6) and a continuous flexible saw blade (3) provided with teeth (8) at one or both edges. A support exposes a section of saw blade (3) that is curved and stabilized by the use of electromagnetic fields in cooperation with rollers. The saw (3) is then configured to make a cut of a desired thickness in a curve parallel the growth rings of a log, in an arc which minimizes the number of knot defects in the board. The compact radius cutting saw (3) may be modified to provide a straight cut by replacing the curved blade with a conventional band saw blade (52). This straight cut saw may optionally include a guide/drive wheel assembly (65, 65a) positioned within or external to the housing. An extendable and retractable sleeve (62) at each open end of the C-shaped housing is provided to further stabilize the saw blade and provide a gentle flow during its course of travel.

A catheter actuation handle for deflecting a distal end of a tubular catheter body having first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body. The handle comprises a first grip portion, a bearing assembly, and an actuator. The first grip portion includes a pivot with a pathway extending through the pivot. The pathway is generally parallel to a longitudinal centerline of the first grip portion. The bearing assembly is located on the first grip portion proximal to the pivot. The actuator is pivotally coupled to the pivot and includes first and second ends that are laterally offset from the longitudinal centerline and are on opposite sides of the centerline from each other. When the distal end of the handle is coupled to the proximal end of the body, the first and second actuation wires extend along the pathway to the bearing assembly. The bearing assembly diverts the first actuation wire to a first connection point on the actuator and the second actuation wire to a second connection point on the actuator.

Spatiotemporal reconstruction in higher dimensions of a moving vascular pulse wave from a plurality of lower dimensional angiographic projections
column13: A plurality of image projections are acquired at faster than cardiac rate. A spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena in three spatial dimensions is generated from two dimensional image projections using physiological coherence at cardiac frequency. Complex valued methods may be used to operate on the plurality of image projections to reconstruct a higher dimensional spatiotemporal object. From a plurality of two spatial dimensional angiographic projections, a 3D spatial reconstruction of moving pulse waves and other cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena is obtained. Reconstruction techniques for angiographic data obtained from biplane angiography devices are also provided herein.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR ELECTRICALLY DESTROYING A SYRINGE NEEDLE
column13: A method and apparatus for sterilizing and destroying a syringe needle includes a rotating needle carriage that receives a needle in a loading position. The needle carriage is rotated downwardly to a cut-off position. At the cut-off position, two opposing contact blades pinch the needle, which electrically connects the positive and negative terminals of a battery. Current flows through the contact blades and the needle, thereby melting the needle. A slight further rotation of the needle carriage causes the contact blades to shear the needle. The sheared portion of the needle then falls into a waste compartment in the bottom of the apparatus. When the syringe is removed from the needle carriage, the needle carriage rotates upwardly and returns to the loading position.

column13: A method and apparatus for removing the needle portion of a hypodermic syringe and simultaneously sterilizing and destroying the needle portion of a hypodermic syringe, eliminating the risk of infection by microorganisms that may be present in or on the needle. When a syringe is inserted into the apparatus, the needle is heated to a temperature sufficient to inactivate any virus, bacteria, yeast, or other microorganism remaining on or within the needle. The needle also is cut at the location of melting so that the needle is removed from the remaining portion of the syringe. Heating and cutting elements (146, 165a) are part of a disposable cartridge (112), which also contains the cut-off needle portions.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR PROVIDING MAGNETIC TUNNELING JUNCTIONS USABLE IN SPIN TRANSFER TORQUE MAGNETIC MEMORIES
column13: A method and system provide a magnetic junction. A free layer, a symmetry filter, and a pinned layer are provided. The free layer has a magnetic moment switchable between stable states when a write current is passed through the magnetic junction. The symmetry filter transmits charge carriers having a first symmetry with higher probability than charge carriers having another symmetry. The symmetry filter resides between the free layer and the pinned layer. The free layer and/or the pinned layer lies in a plane, has the charge carriers of the first symmetry in a spin channel at a Fermi level, lacks the charge carriers of the first symmetry at the Fermi level in another spin channel, and has a nonzero magnetic moment component perpendicular to the plane. The free layer and/or the pinned layer and the symmetry filter has at least one lattice mismatch of less than seven percent.

column13: 21,459. Butler, W. J. Sept. 20. Sewing - machines; governing needle thread. - An improved take - up is provided for machines of the type described in Specification 3705/09, consisting of two levers pivoted to the machine head and having arms provided with rollers to engage slots in a vertically reciprocating needle - bar. The levers 11, 14 are pivoted at 17, 18, and their arms 19, 20 are provided with rollers 21, 22 working in horizontal slots 25, 26 in the needle-bar 27. The thread passes from the tension 4, through guides 5, 6 to the roller 10 of the lever 11, then under the pulley 12 in the guide 6, to the roller 13 of the lever 14, from whence it passes through the guide 15 to the needle. Needles, driving.-The needle-bar 27 is reciprocated by connexion through a fork 44 and roller 42 with a pivoted lever 40 which is provided with a curved slot 39 in which works a roller 38 mounted on a disk 36. The disk 36 is mounted on a shaft having a disk at its other end which is operated by a crank-and-pin connexion from the driving-shaft.

The discovery that contrast in blood vessels varies at cardiac frequency in magnitude and phase, which may be visualized as a spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena, enables processes for increasing the signal to noise ratio or equivalently the content of an angiogram. The organization of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase enables equivalent information on anatomy and physiology to be obtained with less dose of injected chemical contrast agent, less x-ray dose, or less navigation of the injecting catheter within blood vessels. The cardiac frequency magnitude and phase is organized so that the arterial and venous subsystems of circulation have coherence at cardiac frequency. This enables processes for diagnosing deficits that involve alterations in the transit of blood from the arterial to the venous subsystems of circulation. Furthermore, the discovery of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase organization enables the design and manufacture of lighter and more portable angiography equipment.

Improved apparatus and method of removing a needle from a syringe
Reconstructing cardiac frequency phenomena in angiographic data
column13: Techniques are provided for reconstructing cardiac frequency phenomena from a sequence of angiographic images, i.e., two-dimensional projection images acquired at faster than cardiac rate (greater than two-fold), and analyzed to provide a spatiotemporal reconstruction of moving vascular pulse waves according to that projection. In aspects, a cardiac frequency bandpass filter and/or a Eulerian magnification may be applied to the angiographic data to output the spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena.

column12: Method of Equipoise Enrollment of Subjects in Clinical Trials
column13: In a method of enrollment selection of subjects for a clinical trial, a plurality of physician investigators is polled regarding each subject of a plurality of subjects. Responses of the plurality of physician investigators are aggregated for each subject. A subject of the plurality of subjects is enrolled in response to the subject having an aggregate of responses for the clinical trial that exceeds a predetermined minimum value of responses for the clinical trial.

column13: 15,630. Marks, E. C. R., [Butler, W. J.]. Sept. 20, 1909. [Addition to 3705/09.] Sewing-machines; lock-stitching by hooks.- Improved hook and spool - case mechanism is provided for use in machines of the type described in the parent Specification. A rotary hook 58 is mounted on a shaft 55 driven by bevel gearing from the under-shaft of the machine, and is provided with an upper hook 59, a circumferential catch 61, and a lower hook 62. The base has a rim 64 provided with a gap in front of the hook 62, and with an internal groove, part of the rim being removable to permit the withdrawal of the spool-case 67, which has a rim 72 engaging the groove. The spool-case 67 carries an ordinary spool of thread on a central pin integral with the base, and is held from rotation by a lug 74 engaging a slot 75 in the underside of the needle-plate 76. A tension spring 77<a> and tension holes 79, 80<a>, 81 are provided, and the rib 72 has a portion cut away and is formed into a hook 82, behind which is a notch 83. The needle-loop 60 is first entered by the hook 59, and is then spread until it is caught by the lower hook 62, and its inner side held by the hook 82 or the notch 83 while its outer side is carried round by the catch 61 to form a lock with the thread of the spool.

column12: TEMPORAL CALIBRATION OF AN ANGIOGRAPHIC IMAGING SYSTEM
column13: Angiographic data is obtained by injecting a chemical contrast agent intravascularly, and imaging passage of the contrast as a function of time, thereby generating a sequence of images. To correct error from uncalibrated timestamps embedded in the image metadata, radio-opaque markers are used to generate a watermark embedding timestamp data in obtained images. The radio-opaque markers cause opacification on the x-ray images in the form of dynamic watermarks that encode timestamps. The positions of the markers in the watermark (cast from the radio-opaque markers) are then processed and analyzed to generate an accurate timestamp for the image. By generating an accurate timestamp, synchronized calculations of the images with other data sources are provided.

The present invention is directed to a bird collision avoidance system, wherein the bird collision avoidance system is installed on an aircraft and comprises a bird detection unit and an associated bird repelling unit, wherein, the bird repelling unit comprises at least one soudn emitter to generate a sound signal having a variable frequency, focussed beam pattern which is directed along a project flight path of an aircraft. The advantage of using sound signal having a focussed beam pattern is that the beam can be focussed substantially directly at a bird in the projected flight path of the aircraft and can be used to repel the bird away from the projected flight path of the aircraft. By focussing the beam only at the bird in the projected flight path of the aircraft, other birds in the vicinity but not in the projected flight path of the aircraft will not hear the sound signal, and, therefore habituation to the sound signal will be slower than with omni-directional noise emitters as known from the prior art. A modulated ultrasound signal signal may be used as the sound signal having a focussed beam pattern. The bird collision avoidance system may also be mounted on wind turbines. <Figure 1>

An angiogram is a study of blood vessels where an angiographic chemical contrast agent is injected while a sequence of images (typically x-rays) are obtained. The contrast pattern on the sequence of images provides information about the vascular anatomy and physiology. The discovery that contrast in blood vessels varies at cardiac frequency in magnitude and phase, which may be visualized as a spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena, enables a set of processes for increasing the signal to noise ratio or equivalently the informational content of an angiogram. In this invention, the organization of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase enables equivalent information on anatomy and physiology to be obtained with less dose of injected chemical contrast agent, less x-ray dose, and/or less navigation of the injecting catheter within blood vessels. The cardiac frequency magnitude and phase is organized so that the arterial and venous subsystems of circulation have coherence at cardiac frequency. This enables processes for diagnosing deficits of circulation that involve alterations in the transit of blood from the arterial to the venous subsystems of circulation. Furthermore, the discovery of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase organization enables the design and manufacture of lighter and more portable angiography equipment.

혈관조영 데이터는 화학 조영제를 혈관 내로 주입하고, 조영제의 통과를 시간의 함수로서 이미징함으로써 얻어지고, 그에 의해 이미지들의 시퀀스를 생성한다. 이미지 메타데이터에 내장된 교정되지 않은 타임스탬프(timestamp)들의 오류를 정정하기 위해, 무선 불투과성 마커(radio-opaque marker)들은 얻어진 이미지들에 타임스탬프 데이터를 내장하는 워터마크를 생성하기 위해 사용된다. 무선 불투과성 마커들은 타임스탬프들을 인코딩하는 동적 워터마크들의 형태로 엑스레이 이미지들에서의 불투명화를 야기한다. 워터마크(무선 불투과성 마커들로부터 만들어짐)에 있는 마커들의 위치들은 그 다음, 이미지에 대한 정확한 타임스탬프를 생성하기 위해 프로세싱되고 분석된다. 정확한 타임스탬프를 생성함으로써, 다른 데이터 소스들과의 이미지들의 동기화된 산출들이 제공된다.

column12: RECONSTRUCTING CARDIAC FREQUENCY PHENOMENA IN ANGIOGRAPHIC DATA

column12: DEVICE AND METHOD FOR SPATIOTEMPORAL RECONSTRUCTION OF A MOVING VASCULAR PULSE WAVE IN THE BRAIN AND OTHER ORGANS
column13: The brain appears to have organized cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena with such coherence as to qualify as vascular pulse waves. Separate arterial and venous vascular pulse waves may be resolved. This disclosure states the method of extracting a spatiotemporal reconstruction of the cardiac frequency phenomena present in an angiogram obtained at faster than cardiac frequency. A wavelet transform is applied to each of the pixel-wise time signals of the angiogram. If there is motion alias then instead a high frequency resolution wavelet transform of the overall angiographic time intensity curve is cross-correlated to high temporal resolution wavelet transforms of the pixel-wise time signals. The result is filtered for cardiac wavelet scale then pixel-wise inverse wavelet transformed. This gives a complex-valued spatiotemporal grid of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena. It may be rendered with a brightness-hue color model or subjected to further analysis.

column12: Intrinsic contrast optical cross-correlated wavelet angiography
column13: A time sequenced series of optical images of a patient is obtained at a rate faster than cardiac frequency, wherein the time sequenced series of images capture one or more physical properties of intrinsic contrast. A cross-correlated signal from the patient is obtained. A cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis is applied to the time sequenced series of optical images to yield a spatiotemporal representation of cardiac frequency phenomena. The cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis comprises performing a wavelet transform on the time-sequenced series of optical images to obtain a wavelet transformed signal, cross-correlating the wavelet transformed signal with the cross- correland signal to obtain a cross-correlated signal, filtering the cross-correlated, signal at cardiac frequency to obtain a filtered signal, and performing an inverse wavelet transform on the filtered signal to obtain a spatiotemporal representation of the time sequenced series of optical images. Images of the cardiac frequency phenomena are generated.

column12: SPATIOTEMPORAL RECONSTRUCTION IN HIGHER DIMENSIONS OF A MOVING VASCULAR PULSE WAVE FROM A PLURALITY OF LOWER DIMENSIONAL ANGIOGRAPHIC PROJECTIONS
column13: A plurality of image projections are acquired at faster than cardiac rate. A spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena in three spatial dimensions is generated from two dimensional image projections using physiological coherence at cardiac frequency. Complex valued methods may be used to operate on the plurality of image projections to reconstruct a higher dimensional spatiotemporal object. From a plurality of two spatial dimensional angiographic projections, a 3D spatial reconstruction of moving pulse waves and other cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena is obtained. Reconstruction techniques for angiographic data obtained from biplane angiography devices are also provided herein.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR ELECTRICALLY DESTROYING A SYRINGE NEEDLE
column13: After a needle is received in a loading position, the needle carriage (210) is rotated downwardly to a cutoff position. At the cutoff position, two opposing contact blades (220, 230) pinch the needle, which electrically connects the positive and negative terminals of a battery. Current flows through the contact blades (220, 230) and the needle, thereby melting the needle. A slight further rotation of the needle carriage (210) causes the contact blades (220, 230) to shear the needle. The sheared portion of the needle then falls into a waste compartment. When the syringe is removed from the needle carriage (210), the needle carriage (210) rotates upwardly and returns to the loading position. Torsion spring (236) provides constant pressure against a contact blade (230) to maintain the needle carriage (210) in the loading position in the absence of any downward pressure.

An improved piston shaft seal assembly and seal arrangement therein for end-of-car hydraulic cushioning units including an improved seal retainer, an improved first oil scraper abutting the improved seal retainer, an improved reinforced oil seal abutting the improved first seal retainer and a second improved oil seal abutting the improved reinforced oil seal. Optionally, the improved piston shaft seal assembly may include an annular spacer.

column12: PORTABLE LIGHT SYSTEM FOR PERFORMING QUALITY CONTROL
column13: A mobile surface inspection system having a base, at least one extendable arm coupled to the base, a hollow tubular member coupled to the base, and a processor, and a method of using the same. The base has at least one front leg, at least one back leg, and at least one wheel. The extendable arm has four extension members and there is a pivotable joint connected to the fourth extension member. A light fixture is removably connected to the pivotable joint. The processor is configured to receive an image of the surface when illuminated by the light fixture, apply a high-pass filter to the image, identify surface imperfections from the filtered image. and output a position for each of the surface imperfections.

column12: DEVICE AND METHOD FOR SPATIOTEMPORAL RECONSTRUCTION OF A MOVING VASCULAR PULSE WAVE IN THE BRAIN AND OTHER ORGANS
column13: The brain appears to have organized cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena with such coherence as to qualify as vascular pulse waves. Separate arterial and venous vascular pulse waves may be resolved. This disclosure states the method of extracting a spatiotemporal reconstruction of the cardiac frequency phenomena present in an angiogram obtained at faster than cardiac frequency. A wavelet transform is applied to each of the pixel-wise time signals of the angiogram. If there is motion alias then instead a high frequency resolution wavelet transform of the overall angiographic time intensity curve is cross-correlated to high temporal resolution wavelet transforms of the pixel-wise time signals. The result is filtered for cardiac wavelet scale then pixel-wise inverse wavelet transformed. This gives a complex-valued spatiotemporal grid of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena. It may be rendered with a brightness-hue color model or subjected to further analysis.

column12: Method and apparatus for electrically destroying a syringe needle
column13: A method and apparatus for sterilizing and destroying a syringe needle includes a rotating needle carriage that receives a needle in a loading position. The needle carriage is rotated downwardly to a cut-off position. At the cut-off position, two opposing contact blades pinch the needle, which electrically connects the positive and negative terminals of a battery. Current flows through the contact blades and the needle, thereby melting the needle. A slight further rotation of the needle carriage causes the contact blades to shear the needle. The sheared portion of the needle then falls into a waste compartment in the bottom of the apparatus. When the syringe is removed from the needle carriage, the needle carriage rotates upwardly and returns to the loading position.

column12: RECONSTRUCTING CARDIAC FREQUENCY PHENOMENA IN ANGIOGRAPHIC DATA
RECONSTRUCTING CARDIAC FREQUENCY PHENOMENA IN ANGIOGRAPHIC DATA
column13: Techniques are provided for reconstructing cardiac frequency phenomena from a sequence of angiographic images, i.e., two-dimensional projection images acquired at faster than cardiac rate (greater than two-fold), and analyzed to provide a spatiotemporal reconstruction of moving vascular pulse waves according to that projection. In aspects, a cardiac frequency bandpass filter and/or a Eulerian magnification may be applied to the angiographic data to output the spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena.

A variable pitch propeller module for an aero gas turbine engine powerplant
column13: The module (11) comprises a first and second multi-bladed propeller (36, 38) arranged to be driven by gas turbine engine(s) in opposite rotational directions I reduction gear means (30) and shafts (19, 32, 34). First and second drums (66, 78) rotatably mounted on the propeller hubs (60, 72) are arranged to rotate the blades of the propellers via recirculating ball thread and nut arrangements (67, 79). A hydraulic motor (62) is mounted coaxially on and rotates with the second propeller (38), and is arranged to drive the drums (66, 78) via a pitch change gear assembly (86). A hydraulic fluid feed tube (80) extends coaxially through the reduction gear means (30) and both propellers to supply hydraulic fluid to the hydraulic motor (82). An annular sleeve (162) is positioned coaxially on the tube (80). The feed tube (80) and the sleeve (162) are relatively movable axially and each has passages therein so that relative movement between the feed tube (80) and sleeve (162) controls the flow of hydraulic fluid to the hydraulic motor (82) and thereby varies the pitch of both sets of blades. Details of sun and planet gearing for the reduction gear means and for the pitch change gear assembly are disclosed. …<IMAGE>…

column13: A steerable catheter or sheath control handle for steering a distal end of a tubular catheter body or sheath body having first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body comprises a grip portion, a bearing assembly, and an actuator. The first grip potion includes a pivot and an actuation wire pathway. The bearing assembly is located on the grip portion proximal to the pivot. The actuator is pivotally coupled to the pivot and includes first and second ends that are on opposite sides of the centerline from each other. When the distal end of the handle is coupled to the proximal end of the body, the first and second actuation wires extend along the pathway to the bearing assembly. The bearing assembly diverts the first actuation wire to a first connection point on the actuator and the second actuation wire to a second connection point on the actuator.

A steerable catheter or sheath includes a catheter or sheath body defining a longitudinal axis; first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body; and a control handle coupled to the body for steering a distal end of the body. The control handle includes a grip portion including a pivot; a wire diverting assembly located on the grip portion at a location separate from the pivot; and an actuator assembly coupled to the pivot and configured for pivotal movement in a single plane. The wire diverting assembly can include first and second actuation wire connection locations that are disposed on opposite sides of the longitudinal axis. The first and second actuation wires can extend toward the wire diverting assembly in a first orientation, and the wire diverting assembly can change the first orientation to a second orientation that is at an angle to the first orientation.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR ELECTRICALLY DESTROYING A SYRINGE NEEDLE
column13: This invention is directed to a method and apparatus for electrically destroying a syringe needle. The apparatus includes a housing (12) having a burn chamber (14) with a first electrical contact (33) with a conical shaped port (40) mounted on a front face wall (32) of the burn chamber (14) and a second electrical contact (53) made of a block secured to the burn chamber (14) is used to destroy a hypodermic needle (50). The conical shaped port (40) and an opening (37) are sized to receive the metal needle portion (42), the neck portion (44), shoulder portion (46) and body portion (48) of the hypodermic needle (50). A battery (78) is used to energize the contacts (33, 53). When the hypodermic needle (50) is in the opening (37) the length of the needle (50) is in contact with the second contact (53) melting of at least most of the needle's length, with the resulting melted waste falling into a tray (70).

column12: Improvements in Apparatus for Extracting Gold by Means of Mercury.
INTRINSIC CONTRAST OPTICAL CROSS-CORRELATED WAVELET ANGIOGRAPHY
INTRINSIC CONTRAST OPTICAL CROSS-CORRELATED WAVELET ANGIOGRAPHY
column13: A time sequenced series of optical images of a patient is obtained at a rate faster than cardiac frequency, wherein the time sequenced series of images capture one or more physical properties of intrinsic contrast. A cross-correland signal from the patient is obtained. A cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis is applied to the time sequenced series of optical images to yield a spatiotemporal representation of cardiac frequency phenomena The cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis comprises performing a wavelet transform on the time-sequenced series of optical images to obtain a wavelet transformed signal, cross-correlating the wavelet transformed signal with the cross-correland signal to obtain a cross-correlated signal, filtering the cross-correlated signal at cardiac frequency to obtain a filtered signal, and performing an inverse wavelet transform on the filtered signal to obtain a spatiotemporal representation of the time sequenced series of optical images. Images of the cardiac frequency phenomena are generated.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR DESTROYING A SYRINGE NEEDLE
column13: A method and apparatus for destroying a syringe needle, having a housing, first and second walls in opposed relationship in the housing and defining therebetween a needle burn chamber, the distance between the first and second surfaces being at least the length of the needle, the first surface defining a first opening therethrough, needle receiving means in the chamber movable between the first and second surfaces and defining a second opening therethrough which is coaxial with the first opening, a first electrical contact on the needle receiving means, a second electrical contact on the second surface and being in registry with the second opening, power means connected to the first and second contacts, a waste collecting means disposed in the housing beneath and in communication with the burn chamber, the waste collecting means being removable from the housing, and means for normally biasing the needle receiving means toward the first opening; so that when the needle is inserted through the first and second openings to be in contacting relationship to the needle receiving means and the needle receiving means is moved toward the second surface, the tip of the needle engages the second contact closing the circuit between the contacts and melting the needle along at least most of its length with the resultant melted waste falling into the waste collecting means.

column12: Spatiotemporal reconstruction of a moving vascular pulse wave from a plurality of lower dimensional angiographic projections
METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR ELECTRICALLY DESTROYING A SYRINGE NEEDLE
column13: After a needle is received in a loading position, the needle carriage (210) is rotated downwardly to a cutoff position. At the cutoff position, two opposing contact blades (220, 230) pinch the needle, which electrically connects the positive and negative terminals of a battery. Current flows through the contact blades (220, 230) and the needle, thereby melting the needle. A slight further rotation of the needle carriage (210) causes the contact blades (220, 230) to shear the needle. The sheared portion of the needle then falls into a waste compartment. When the syringe is removed from the needle carriage (210), the needle carriage (210) rotates upwardly and returns to the loading position. Torsion spring (236) provides constant pressure against a contact blade (230) to maintain the needle carriage (210) in the loading position in the absence of any downward pressure.

column12: MACHINE FOR APPLYING CEMENT TO CAN-CAPS.

column13: The present invention is a catheter actuation handle for deflecting a distal end of a tubular catheter body having first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body. The handle comprises a first grip portion, a bearing assembly, and an actuator. The first grip potion includes a pivot with a pathway extending through the pivot. The pathway is generally parallel to a longitudinal centerline of the first grip portion. The bearing assembly is located on the first grip portion proximal to the pivot. The actuator is pivotally coupled to the pivot and includes first and second ends that are laterally offset from the longitudinal centerline and are on opposite sides of the centerline from each other. When the distal end of the handle is coupled to the proximal end of the body, the first and second actuation wires extend along the pathway to the bearing assembly. The bearing assembly diverts the first actuation wire to a first connection point on the actuator and the second actuation wire to a second connection point on the actuator.

column12: Improvements in Gaff and Clearing Tackle for Anglers.
column13: 10,507. Butler, W. J. May 21. Gaff-hooks; clearing-appliances. -A length of wire is bent into a coil a with one end formed into a hook e and the other weighted at c. To gaff a fish, the coil a is threaded on the running line h, and lowered by a line i, a sudden pull upon which tilts the hook into the position shown in broken lines, and secures the fish. In a modification, the, hook is attached to the lower part of the coil.

29,065. Butler, H. W. Dec. 30. Dry batteries.-Into the pot (zinc) of the battery is introduced a pasty separating-mass consisting of a mixture of exciting-salt, such as salammoniac with or without a small proportion of a hygroscopic salt such as zinc chloride, starch, or starchy matter, for example ground maize, or an equivalent of starch, and a material such as plaster of Paris or cement which will give the requisite consistency to the mass. By means of, a central plunger, the paste is caused to form a lining to the pot, and it is then cooked by the application of heat and moisture, for example by the admission of steam. After cooling, a carbon element is inserted, the space between it and the lining being packed with depolarizer.

The present invention is a catheter actuation handle for deflecting a distal end of a tubular catheter body having first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body. The handle comprises a first grip portion, a bearing assembly, and an actuator. The first grip potion includes a pivot with a pathway extending through the pivot. The pathway is generally parallel to a longitudinal centerline of the first grip portion. The bearing assembly is located on the first grip portion proximal to the pivot. The actuator is pivotally coupled to the pivot and includes first and second ends that are laterally offset from the longitudinal centerline and are on opposite sides of the centerline from each other. When the distal end of the handle is coupled to the proximal end of the body, the first and second actuation wires extend along the pathway to the bearing assembly. The bearing assembly diverts the first actuation wire to a first connection point on the actuator and the second actuation wire to a second connection point on the actuator.

column12: SPATIOTEMPORAL RECONSTRUCTION OF A MOVING VASCULAR PULSE WAVE FROM A PLURALITY OF LOWER DIMENSIONAL ANGIOGRAPHIC PROJECTIONS
column13: A plurality of image projections are acquired at faster than cardiac rate. A spatiotemporal reconstruction of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena in three spatial dimensions is generated from two dimensional image projections using physiological coherence at cardiac frequency. Complex valued methods may be used to operate on the plurality of image projections to reconstruct a higher dimensional spatiotemporal object. From a plurality of two spatial dimensional angiographic projections, a 3D spatial reconstruction of moving pulse waves and other cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena is obtained. Reconstruction techniques for angiographic data obtained from biplane angiography devices are also provided herein.

column13: The discovery that contrast in blood vessels varies at cardiac frequency in magnitude and phase enables a set of processes for increasing the signal to noise ratio or equivalently the informational content of an angiogram. In this invention, the organization of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase enables equivalent information on anatomy and physiology to be obtained with less dose of injected chemical contrast agent, less x-ray dose, and/or less navigation of the injecting catheter within blood vessels. The cardiac frequency magnitude and phase is organized so that the arterial and venous subsystems of circulation have coherence at cardiac frequency. This enables processes for diagnosing deficits of circulation that involve alterations in the transit of blood from the arterial to the venous subsystems of circulation. Furthermore, the discovery of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase organization enables the design and manufacture of lighter and more portable angiography equipment.

column12: Intrinsic contrast optical cross-correlated wavelet angiography
column13: A time sequenced series of optical images of a patient is obtained at a rate faster than cardiac frequency, wherein the time sequenced series of images capture one or more physical properties of intrinsic contrast. A cross-correlated signal from the patient is obtained. A cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis is applied to the time sequenced series of optical images to yield a spatiotemporal representation of cardiac frequency phenomena. The cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis comprises performing a wavelet transform on the time-sequenced series of optical images to obtain a wavelet transformed signal, cross-correlating the wavelet transformed signal with the cross- correland signal to obtain a cross-correlated signal, filtering the cross-correlated, signal at cardiac frequency to obtain a filtered signal, and performing an inverse wavelet transform on the filtered signal to obtain a spatiotemporal representation of the time sequenced series of optical images. Images of the cardiac frequency phenomena are generated.

A steerable catheter or sheath includes a catheter or sheath body defining a longitudinal axis; first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body; and a control handle coupled to the body for steering a distal end of the body. The control handle includes a grip portion including a pivot; a wire diverting assembly located on the grip portion at a location separate from the pivot; and an actuator assembly coupled to the pivot and configured for pivotal movement in a single plane. The wire diverting assembly can include first and second actuation wire connection locations that are disposed on opposite sides of the longitudinal axis. The first and second actuation wires can extend toward the wire diverting assembly in a first orientation, and the wire diverting assembly can change the first orientation to a second orientation that is at an angle to the first orientation.

column12: Temporal calibration of an angiographic imaging system
column13: Angiographic data is obtained by injecting a chemical contrast agent intravascularly, and imaging passage of the contrast as a function of time, thereby generating a sequence of images. To correct error from uncalibrated timestamps embedded in the image metadata, radio-opaque markers are used to generate a watermark embedding timestamp data in obtained images. The radio-opaque markers cause opacification on the x-ray images in the form of dynamic watermarks that encode timestamps. The positions of the markers in the watermark (cast from the radio-opaque markers) are then processed and analyzed to generate an accurate timestamp for the image. By generating an accurate timestamp, synchronized calculations of the images with other data sources are provided.

column12: Device and method for spatiotemporal reconstruction of a moving vascular pulse wave in the brain and other organs
column13: The brain appears to have organized cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena with such coherence as to qualify as vascular pulse waves. Separate arterial and venous vascular pulse waves may be resolved. This disclosure states the method of extracting a spatiotemporal reconstruction of the cardiac frequency phenomena present in an angiogram obtained at faster than cardiac frequency. A wavelet transform is applied to each of the pixel-wise time signals of the angiogram. If there is motion alias then instead a high frequency resolution wavelet transform of the overall angiographic time intensity curve is cross-correlated to high temporal resolution wavelet transforms of the pixel-wise time signals. The result is filtered for cardiac wavelet scale then pixel-wise inverse wavelet transformed. This gives a complex-valued spatiotemporal grid of cardiac frequency angiographic phenomena. It may be rendered with a brightness-hue color model or subjected to further analysis.

column12: Improved Means or Apparatus for Adjusting the Weight on the Shafts of Two Wheeled Road Vehicles.
Temporal calibration of an angiographic imaging system
column13: Angiographic data is obtained by injecting a chemical contrast agent intravascularly, and imaging passage of the contrast as a function of time, thereby generating a sequence of images. To correct error from uncalibrated timestamps embedded in the image metadata, radio-opaque markers are used to generate a watermark embedding timestamp data in obtained images. The radio-opaque markers cause opacification on the x-ray images in the form of dynamic watermarks that encode timestamps. The positions of the markers in the watermark (cast from the radio-opaque markers) are then processed and analyzed to generate an accurate timestamp for the image. By generating an accurate timestamp, synchronized calculations of the images with other data sources are provided.

column13: The discovery that contrast in blood vessels varies at cardiac frequency in magnitude and phase enables a set of processes for increasing the signal to noise ratio or equivalently the informational content of an angiogram. In this invention, the organization of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase enables equivalent information on anatomy and physiology to be obtained with less dose of injected chemical contrast agent, less x-ray dose, and/or less navigation of the injecting catheter within blood vessels. The cardiac frequency magnitude and phase is organized so that the arterial and venous subsystems of circulation have coherence at cardiac frequency. This enables processes for diagnosing deficits of circulation that involve alterations in the transit of blood from the arterial to the venous subsystems of circulation. Furthermore, the discovery of cardiac frequency magnitude and phase organization enables the design and manufacture of lighter and more portable angiography equipment.

The present invention is a catheter actuation handle for deflecting a distal end of a tubular catheter body having first and second actuation wires extending from a proximal end of the body. The handle comprises a first grip portion, a bearing assembly, and an actuator. The first grip potion includes a pivot with a pathway extending through the pivot. The pathway is generally parallel to a longitudinal centerline of the first grip portion. The bearing assembly is located on the first grip portion proximal to the pivot. The actuator is pivotally coupled to the pivot and includes first and second ends that are laterally offset from the longitudinal centerline and are on opposite sides of the centerline from each other. When the distal end of the handle is coupled to the proximal end of the body, the first and second actuation wires extend along the pathway to the bearing assembly. The bearing assembly diverts the first actuation wire to a first connection point on the actuator and the second actuation wire to a second connection point on the actuator.

Method and apparatus for electrically destroying a syringe needle
column13: A method and apparatus for sterilizing and destroying a syringe needle, having a housing, first and second walls in opposed relationship in the housing and defining therebetween a needle burn chamber, the distance between the first and second surfaces being at least the length of the needle, the first surface defining an opening therethrough, a needle receiver in the chamber, a first electrical contact on the needle receiver, a second electrical contact comprising an electrically conductive surface secured within the burn chamber and or added substantially perpendicular to the face of the needle receiver and the surface in alignment with the central line of the needle receiver, power source connected to the first and second contacts and, a waste collector disposed in the housing beneath and in communication with the burn chamber, the waste collector being removable from the housing; so that when the needle is inserted through the opening, it is in contacting relationship with the first electrical contact, the length of the needle then engages the second electrical contact closing the circuit between the contacts and melting the needle along at least most of its length with the resultant melted waste falling into the waste collector.

column12: Improvements in or relating to demountable boxes or cases
column13: 639,789. Boxes. MINISTER OF SUPPLY. July 23, 1947, No. 19821. [Class 18] The sides, bottom and lid of a knockdown box are beaded for inter-engagement with the beaded edges of separate corner clamps by which they are joined together. The box panel beading 3 and corner clamps beading 7 are shaped to permit engagement by lateral pressing but dis-engagement by sliding only. To reduce the sliding movement necessary, and to permit the rapid removal of the box lid, sections of the beading are serrated by cuts and complementary grooves 18 which are aligned by sliding one member, to permit the turned-over part 5 of the outer bead to clear the inner bead. In assembling the box, the sides are joined by corner clamps 10 and pressed into engagement with the box bottom, the serrated beading being arranged on the upper edges of the sides. Corner clamps 10 are positioned on the lid and the lid is pressed into engagement with the sides. The corner clamps 10 forming the horizontal edges each carry a portion 15 which covers a point of juncture of three box edges and may incorporate securing means such as a screwed bolt engaging adjacent corner clamps. In removing the lid, the upper corner clamps are slid to bring the serrations into alignment. The box panels may be reinforced by corrugations or additional panels secured thereto. The corner clamps 10 may be integral with the portions 15 and be moulded or drawn.

column12: Method and system for providing magnetic tunneling junctions usable in spin transfer torque magnetic memories
column13: A method and system provide a magnetic junction. A free layer, a symmetry filter, and a pinned layer are provided. The free layer has a magnetic moment switchable between stable states when a write current is passed through the magnetic junction. The symmetry filter transmits charge carriers having a first symmetry with higher probability than charge carriers having another symmetry. column13: 23,715. Butler, W. H. Nov. 28. Packeting or parcelling cigarettes, cigarette holders, &c.-Boxes are formed from suitably-scored and cut blanks and filled with cigarettes or other articles and then inserted into shells or covers by the apparatus shown in side view in Fig. 1 and in part plan in Fig. 3. The blanks are stored in a magazine D, from which they are partially ejected into a channel E by means of pushers 19 on a plunger 18, being then carried along by projections 27 on an endless belt A. The blank consists of a bottom part 2, side flap 4, and flap 5, the other end flap 8, being integral with the cover 3 having flaps or flanges 7 which fall outside the sides 4. The sides 4 are turned up by means of inclines, as the blank is fed along, and, when under the magazine F containing the cigarettes &c., a definite quantity of these is filled into it. The magazine F is, in the present instance, partitioned to hold vertical rows of cigarettes and also an end row of cigarette holders of the kind which are adapted to be nested together, each set nested together being placed, as regards the direction in which they taper, in the reverse position to the next set, so that the top surface of each pair of sets will be horizontal. The cigarettes are fed into the magazine, in an ordinary manner, from the hopper 34. The nested holders are fed to the magazine along grooves in inclined tables 46 by means of rollers 48, 49. A gripper 57 on each end of a reciprocating carriage 58 takes off from the nested line of holders the desired number, in this instance five, to be fed in the nested position into the magazine, the vertical row being formed of several such sets which are fed into the magazine from the right and left, alternately. A clamp holds the next holder of the nest, to permit the removal of the first five from it. The cigarettes and holders being delivered into the box by means of a plunger, the end 8 and cover part 3 of the blank are folded over the contents, by means of a folder or finger mounted on the shaft 73 and operating vertically in the path of the box. The end 5 is turned up by means of folders I, which are pivoted to the belt A and are operated by a projection on the table, and the projecting portion is turned down on the cover 3 by means of toothed wheels J or swinging arms. The box, thus filled and formed, is next pushed into the shell. The shells are piled in a flat or collapsed condition in a magazine K, from which they are ejected by a plunger. The shell, on being ejected, is slightly opened by means of cams, to ensure its passage over a wedge-shaped device, through which the filled box is forced into the shell. The covered box then falls down a shoot from the machine.

INTRINSIC CONTRAST OPTICAL CROSS-CORRELATED WAVELET ANGIOGRAPHY
column13: A time sequenced series of optical images of a patient is obtained at a rate faster than cardiac frequency, wherein the time sequenced series of images capture one or more physical properties of intrinsic contrast. A cross-correlated signal from the patient is obtained. A cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis is applied to the time sequenced series of optical images to yield a spatiotemporal representation of cardiac frequency phenomena. The cross-correlated wavelet transform analysis comprises performing a wavelet transform on the time-sequenced series of optical images to obtain a wavelet transformed signal, cross-correlating the wavelet transformed signal with the cross- correland signal to obtain a cross-correlated signal, filtering the cross-correlated, signal at cardiac frequency to obtain a filtered signal, and performing an inverse wavelet transform on the filtered signal to obtain a spatiotemporal representation of the time sequenced series of optical images. Images of the cardiac frequency phenomena are generated.

column13: 1282. Butler, W. H. Jan. 19. Packeting cigarettes &c.-Boxes are made of paper and like material, and cigarettes or other articles are filled or packed into the same by apparatus, such as that shown in Figs. 1,3,6, and 17. The material from which the boxes are made is fed from a roll 3, Fig. 1, to a roller 5 having knives or ribs and scorers, by which the blank is formed as shown in Fig. 3, with bottom 8, side flaps 9, rear flaps 10, 12, and front flaps 13, 15, transverse scores 14, 21, 22, 11, and rounded ends on the flaps. The blanks, which are still integral with one another, are next fed to another part 2 of the machine, Fig. 1, where the further operations are effected, the strip of blanks being allowed to sag or drop down between both parts, so that the strip is fed independently in each part. In the part 2, the strip is fed by a reciprocating frame 25, Figs. 1 and 6, having projections 26, which engage with the side flaps 9 of each blank. The blanks are thus brought into position under the vertically-operating knife 31, by which they are severed, the knife being carried on a walking beam 70 operated by a cam on the " driving- " shaft" 55. The knife also carries projections or pads 36, which hold the strip while the frame 25 makes its backward movement, during which the longitudinal scores 16, dividing the side flaps 9 from the bottom 8, are effected by scoring-rollers carried by the frame. A weighted arm 80 on the walking beam beats down the ends of the cut-off blank to facilitate its engagement with pickers 37 on an endless belt 38 by which the blank is now fed. The blank is thus carried into a trough having sloping sides, by which the side flaps 9 are raised, and, when brought into position under a receptacle 43 containing the cigarettes or other articles, the cigarettes &c. are filled into the partially-folded box by a pusher in the manner described in Specification No. 23,715, A.D. 1899. The rear flap 10 is now set up by a feeder 45 having two arms 46, 47 set at right-angles to one another and pivoted to the belt 38, the arm 47, which hitherto lay flat, being now lifted by means of a cam, against which the arm 46 abuts. The flaps 13, 15 are next raised and the flap 15 folded over the cigarettes &c. by means of folding arms 95, Fig. 17, carried on pivoted supports 49, actuated by a cam, which arms also serve to fold the rear flap 12 over the flap 15, they being suitably curved at both sides to effect this double purpose. The enclosing shells, which are stacked in a collapsed state in a receptacle 53, are now pushed forward to enclose the filled and folded box, by a plate 112 having a shoulder 123, which engages with the bottom shells in succession, the plate being moved forward by the toothed segment 115 through a rack 113, and again brought backward by a spring 120. The shell enters a trough in which it is partially opened, being afterwards fully opened by wedge expanders 125, as described in Specification No. 23,715, A.D. 1899, and is finally pushed over. the box to enclose it, the whole falling from the machine through an aperture 54 when the plate 112 is withdrawn. When, in filling oval cigarettes, it is desired to have the longer axis vertical, the cigarettes are fed from the receptacle 43 through guides having sloping sides. Again, in order to fill the cigarettes so that the longer axes lie horizontal, the receptacle 43 is fitted with vertically-moving partitions, and the bottom of the receptacle is also corrugated to receive them in this position. In this case, two layers of cigarettes are inserted with a sheet of paper between, one layer being first inserted from one receptacle, then a paper sheet fed and cut off from a strip, and, finally, a second layer from another receptacle.

column12: Apparatus and method for removing a needle from a syringe
column13: A method and apparatus for removing the needle portion of a hypodermic syringe and simultaneously sterilizing and destroying the needle portion of a hypodermic syringe, thereby eliminating the risk of infection by microorganisms that may be present in or on the needle. When a syringe is inserted into the apparatus, the needle is heated to a temperature sufficient to melt or at least soften the needle, and sufficient to inactivate any virus, bacteria, yeast, or other microorganism remaining on or within the needle. The needle also is cut at the location of melting so that the needle is removed from the remaining portion of the syringe. The heating and cutting elements are part of a disposable cartridge, which also contains the cut-off needle portions.
